      Who is selling all this underpriced life insurance?
   =20
 =20
We talked on Tuesday about a weird trade. The trade is: A person, usually a=
n older person =E2=80=94=C2=A0call her Alice =E2=80=94 takes out a $5 milli=
on life insurance policy, naming an investor =E2=80=94=C2=A0call him Bob =
=E2=80=94 as the beneficiary. Bob pays Alice a fee for doing this =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0say 3% of the face value of the policy =E2=80=94=C2=A0and also=C2=A0p=
ays=C2=A0the premiums on the policy. Eventually Alice dies, the insurance p=
ays out, and Bob gets the money. If the death benefit is higher than the pr=
emiums that Bob has paid over time =E2=80=94=C2=A0for instance, because Ali=
ce dies a week after taking out the policy =E2=80=94=C2=A0then Bob makes a =
profit. If the death benefit is lower than the premiums =E2=80=94=C2=A0for =
instance, because Alice lives to be 125 =E2=80=94=C2=A0then Bob loses money=
.The thing that most people find weird about this trade is the general icki=
ness of the investor betting on Alice=E2=80=99s death. In fact, this trade =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0it is called STOLI, for stranger-originated life insurance =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0is not allowed in many places; we talked about it Tuesday be=
cause the estate of an=C2=A0Alice=C2=A0(Martha Barotz)=C2=A0was suing a Bob=
 (Apollo Global Management Inc.) to get the $5 million back.=C2=A0But I don=
=E2=80=99t mind ickiness, and the thing that I found weird about the trade =
was different. The thing that I found weird is: How can Bob expect to make =
money on this trade? He is betting on Alice=E2=80=99s life span, with the l=
ife insurance company on the other side; why should he expect to win that b=
et? Presumably Alice is a stranger to him and to the insurance company, and=
 both of them can ask her for her medical history and do physical exams.=C2=
=A0What is Bob=E2=80=99s informational advantage?=C2=A0I wrote:On a deal li=
ke this, the investor has to pay the insurance premiums, it has to pay the =
insured a 3% commission to get her to take out the policy, it has to pay th=
e agent a commission for signing her up,
  [1]
=C2=A0and of course it has to pay lawyers and take the risk that the policy=
 will be invalid. And yet there=E2=80=99s apparently still enough money in =
it to make it a good, securitizable investment. Who is selling all this und=
erpriced life insurance?Several readers wrote in to answer=C2=A0this questi=
on, and the answer is illuminating. Here=E2=80=99s how one reader put it:So=
me large fraction of life insurance policies are not optimally exercised.=
=C2=A0=C2=A0So traditionally life insurance companies sold insurance that w=
as significantly underpriced if the recipient was going to optimally exerci=
se it, and yet profitable because some reasonable fraction of their clients=
 let their policies lapse sub-optimally.=E2=80=9COptimal exercise=E2=80=9D =
is a term from options markets and I suppose it is a little icky to apply i=
t to life insurance. (You =E2=80=9Cexercise=E2=80=9D life insurance by dyin=
g, and it is generally optimal to die as late as possible.) But the point i=
s that a lot of people take out life insurance policies, and then their cir=
cumstances change, they=C2=A0stop paying the premiums and the policy is can=
celed.
  [2]
If you take out a 20-year term life insurance policy, pay premiums for eigh=
t years, stop paying premiums, and then die in Year 10, you will get no dea=
th benefit and the insurance company will keep your eight years of premiums=
. This is =E2=80=9Csuboptimal,=E2=80=9D for you, as a=C2=A0technical financ=
ial matter. But it might have been a perfectly rational decision for you to=
 let the insurance lapse: You took out the insurance thinking your heirs ne=
eded money when you died more than you needed the premiums while you were a=
live, and then your circumstances changed. Maybe you thought you needed 20 =
years of insurance to provide for your minor children, but then they got ch=
ild acting gigs and don=E2=80=99t need the insurance money, and you=E2=80=
=99d rather spend the premiums while you=E2=80=99re alive.But the=C2=A0insu=
rance company=C2=A0doesn=E2=80=99t care about any of that; from the insuran=
ce company=E2=80=99s perspective what happened is that it got eight years o=
f premiums and didn=E2=80=99t have to pay out when you died. You did not ex=
ercise optimally. The insurance company is in an actuarial business; it can=
 predict what percentage of its customers will let their policies lapse. Th=
e percentage is large.
  [3]
 And in a competitive market, it can price this, and does.
  [4]
 The amount you pay for a 20-year term life policy is calculated based on:=
=09The insurance company=E2=80=99s well-informed prediction of when you are=
 likely to die,=C2=A0and=09The insurance company=E2=80=99s well-informed pr=
ediction of when you are likely to stop paying premiums.Bob, in our example=
, is no better at predicting Alice=E2=80=99s death than the insurance compa=
ny is.
  [5]
 But there is an information asymmetry: The insurance company thinks that A=
lice has, say, a 40% chance of letting the policy lapse before she dies, an=
d Bob knows that the actual chance is 0%. He=E2=80=99s paying the premiums,=
 he=E2=80=99s a=C2=A0financial investor, he bought this policy as a bet, hi=
s circumstances are not going to change, he=E2=80=99s going to keep paying =
until he gets the death benefit.
  [6]
 The insurance company priced the policy at, intuitively, a 40% discount to=
 its purely mortality-risk-based value, because it figured there was a 40% =
chance of suboptimal lapse. That 40% discount is =E2=80=94 in expectation, =
over hundreds of policies that he buys =E2=80=94 profit to Bob.A few points=
 about this. One: It=E2=80=99s a big part of why STOLI is often illegal. Co=
urts say that insurance contracts are valid only if they are taken out for =
=E2=80=9Ca legitimate insurance purpose, such as estate planning.=E2=80=9D =
Insurance companies price insurance based on the assumption that real peopl=
e are doing estate planning, and their circumstances might change in ways t=
hat lead to suboptimal exercise. Insurance priced based on a pure bet=C2=A0=
would be more expensive.=C2=A0In fact, there seems to have been a boom in S=
TOLI in the mid-2000s, as the secondary market for life insurance was rampi=
ng up, but it died=C2=A0 out by 2008. The trade we talked about Tuesday was=
 originated in 2006; it=E2=80=99s cleaning up an old STOLI policy, not an a=
ctive trade. Part of the reason for this ramp-up was that, for insurance ca=
rriers and brokers, STOLI looked=C2=A0like a good trade at the time: They g=
ot to write all these big insurance policies! Those policies looked=C2=A0pr=
ofitable, based on historical data. Then they realized they were all underp=
riced and shut it down.Two: This problem is not=C2=A0solely=C2=A0a feature =
of STOLI insurance. We talked on Tuesday about the broader business of inve=
stors buying life insurance policies; Apollo, for instance, manages billion=
s of dollars=E2=80=99 worth of policies. Most of those policies are=C2=A0no=
t=C2=A0STOLI policies; they were taken out by real people for real insuranc=
e purposes, and then, when those peoples=E2=80=99 needs changed, they sold =
the policies to investors. STOLI is frowned upon and often illegal and hard=
 to collect on, but the broader secondary market for insurance policies is =
fine and legitimate and does pay out.=C2=A0But it=E2=80=99s the same proble=
m. Insurance companies bet that X% of their policies will lapse suboptimall=
y. If there is a robust and well-advertised=C2=A0secondary market for the p=
olicies, then this estimate will be much too high: Everyone who takes out a=
n insurance policy and decides to stop paying the premiums will=C2=A0sell=
=C2=A0the policy to an investor, for cash, rather than letting it lapse for=
 nothing.
  [7]
 And so not just STOLI policies, but=C2=A0all=C2=A0policies, will be underp=
riced. On Tuesday I quoted (in a footnote) a 2011 paper by Susan Lorde Mart=
in on =E2=80=9CBetting on the Lives of Strangers: Life Settlements, STOLI, =
and Securitization,=E2=80=9D making this point:The life insurance industry =
argues that its surrender value schedule
  [8]
 and the fact that policyholders allow thirty-eight percent of all policies=
 to lapse (receiving no death benefit)=C2=A0permit life insurance companies=
 to keep premiums as low as they are.=C2=A0Life settlement arrangements mea=
n=C2=A0that policies will not lapse, so insurance carriers will pay death b=
enefits on many more policies than they would be paying otherwise. This wil=
l result in higher premiums for everyone, including those who want only the=
 death risk coverage.The point is that insurance is priced as an individual=
 product sold to=C2=A0people, who are constrained by their circumstances an=
d their access to capital, and who will sometimes make decisions that creat=
e a financial windfall for the insurance companies. But if those people hav=
e access to deep liquid capital markets, then they won=E2=80=99t. And all t=
hat insurance will be mispriced.But that mostly hasn=E2=80=99t happened. Th=
ere are trillions of dollars of life insurance in the US, of which tens of =
billions of dollars of policies are owned by secondary-market investors. Lo=
ts of people still let their life insurance policies lapse; virtually none =
of them instead resell them in the secondary market.=C2=A0The Life Insuranc=
e Settlement Association =E2=80=94=C2=A0a trade organization for the second=
ary market in life insurance =E2=80=94=C2=A0says that its members bought $4=
.35 billion face amount of policies in 2022 in 3,079 transactions, which =
=E2=80=9Crepresent just a tiny fraction of the 9.28 million policies valued=
 at $624 billion that are lapsed or surrendered annually by life insurance =
consumers.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0So the insurance isn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0mispriced, fro=
m the insurance companies=E2=80=99 perspective: They charge a price that ac=
curately reflects the expected behavior of their customers. But it=C2=A0is=
=C2=A0mispriced, for a financial buyer. The buyer (the investor) and the se=
ller (the insurer) can both make money on their zero-sum bet, as long as lo=
ts of other non-financial buyers subsidize them.Third: This is all reminisc=
ent of mortgages? We have=C2=A0talked=C2=A0a=C2=A0few=C2=A0times, as rates =
have gone up, about assumable mortgages. A few months ago, I wrote:The norm=
al US mortgage is a 30-year fixed-rate loan that is prepayable without pena=
lty. If a bank lends you money at 5% and then rates go down to 3%, you will=
 go refinance at 3% and pay back the original 5% loan: The bank won=E2=80=
=99t get to keep its original, now-above-market loan. But if instead rates =
go up to 7%, you don=E2=80=99t have to pay the bank back for 30 years: The =
bank is stuck with its original, now-below-market loan. You have an option =
to reprice when rates go down; the bank does not have an option to reprice =
when rates go up.This is a bummer for the bank, but it is mitigated by the =
fact that you probably=C2=A0won=E2=80=99t=C2=A0wait 30 years to pay back th=
e loan: You=E2=80=99ll probably=C2=A0sell your house, for some non-financia=
l reason (you have kids and need a bigger house; your kids grow up and you =
don=E2=80=99t need such a big house), and then you=E2=80=99ll have to pay b=
ack the loan. The bank is stuck with its below-market loan, but not forever=
; even now, when mortgage rates are 7%, some people still go and pay off th=
eir 3% mortgages. If they didn=E2=80=99t, things would be rough for the ban=
k.If mortgages were always automatically assumable, then when you sold your=
 house you=E2=80=99d let the buyer assume your mortgage, and that 3% mortga=
ge would remain outstanding for 30 years, and the bank would be stuck with =
it, and that would be worse for the bank, so it would have to charge you mo=
re for your mortgage to begin with.The entire US mortgage system is priced =
off the fact that people suboptimally exercise their mortgage prepayment op=
tion: People are=C2=A0constantly=C2=A0prepaying 3% mortgages when mortgage =
rates are 7%, an insane financial decision=C2=A0in isolation=C2=A0but possi=
bly perfectly rational for them=C2=A0in real life.=C2=A0(If you have to mov=
e, for a new job or a new relationship or just a nicer house, you will prob=
ably have to prepay your mortgage.) The average 30-year mortgage actually l=
asts less than 10 years, meaning that there are a lot of suboptimal prepaym=
ents.If you could move without prepaying your mortgage =E2=80=94=C2=A0if yo=
u could just transfer your mortgage to whoever is buying your house =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0then you would, and all cheap mortgages would remain outstanding f=
or 30 years, and=C2=A0the whole mortgage market would be mispriced. Which i=
s why you can=E2=80=99t.
