  [1] Actually the insurance company normally pays the agent, but the econo=
mic point stands: There are a lot of mouths to feed here out of what is ess=
entially a zero-sum bet between the insurance company and the investor.


  [2] That is the normal result in a term life policy. Other insurance prod=
ucts (universal life) have a savings component, and you can stop paying pre=
miums and cash out the savings component (the =E2=80=9Csurrender value=E2=
=80=9D of the policy). In either case though you are effectively losing the=
 actuarial value of your death benefit. I talk about term policies in the t=
ext because they are simpler to understand, but in reality most of the acti=
vity here is in universal life.


  [3] Below, I quote a published estimate of 38%, but I have informally hea=
rd much higher numbers. Here is a 2016 study by Daniel Gottlieb and Kent Sm=
etters finding lapse rates of 2.5% to 7% per year.


  [4] =E2=80=9CThere is substantial anecdotal evidence that insurers take s=
ubsequent profits from lapses into account when setting their premiums,=E2=
=80=9D wrote Gottlieb and Smetters. They provide some numbers: =E2=80=9CThe=
 Society of Actuaries 2006 Annual Meetings held a session on lapse-supporte=
d pricing that included presentations from actuaries employed by several le=
ading insurance companies and consultants. Kevin Howard, Vice President of =
Protective Life Insurance Company, for example, demonstrated the impact of =
lapses on profit margins for a representative male client who bought a leve=
l-premium secondary guarantee universal life policy, with the premium set e=
qual to the average amount paid by such males in August 2006 in the company=
=E2=80=99s sample. Assuming a zero lapse rate, the insurer projected a subs=
tantial negative profit margin, equal to -12.8%. However, at a typical four=
 percent lapse rate, the insurer=E2=80=99s projected profit margin was  13.=
6%, or a 26.4% increase relative to no lapsing.=E2=80=9D That is, the polic=
y is priced at a level that would lose money for the insurer, if every cust=
omer kept paying the premiums. But it makes money for the insurer, because =
many of them don=E2=80=99t.


  [5] He=E2=80=99s also not much *worse*, because he=E2=80=99s a price take=
r on the policy, and in a competitive market the insurance company is going=
 to price the policy based on its best estimate of her mortality risk.


  [6] Realistically Bob is a fund, and even if he runs into financial probl=
ems and can=E2=80=99t keep paying the premiums, he=E2=80=99ll sell the poli=
cy to someone else for its market value.


  [7] At least in many cases, the investor will pay some nonzero amount of =
money for it, because it is underpriced, because it was priced assuming sub=
optimal exercise. But there are exceptions: If you took out a term life pol=
icy when you were sickly and smoking and then got incredibly fit, an invest=
or might not pay you to take over the premiums.


  [8] See footnote 2. Lorde Martin also notes that =E2=80=9CThe life insura=
nce industry contributed to the emergence of the life settlement industry b=
y offering very low surrender value payments to people. One life settlement=
 company claims that, on average, it has paid policy owners about ten times=
 the surrender value offered by the issuing insurance company when the poli=
cy owner wanted to stop paying premiums. One trade association reports that=
 the average settlement is four to six times the surrender value.=E2=80=9D


  [9] From today=E2=80=99s FTC complaint: =E2=80=9COPEC was created in 1960=
 with the stated purpose to =E2=80=98coordinate and unify the petroleum pol=
icies of its Member Countries and ensure the stabilization of oil markets.=
=E2=80=99 OPEC has twelve member nations: Saudi Arabia, Iran, Iraq, Kuwait,=
 Venezuela, Indonesia, Libya, UAE, Algeria, Nigeria, Equatorial Guinea, and=
 Congo. Ten additional countries=E2=80=94including Russia=E2=80=94affiliate=
d with OPEC in 2016 to create what is now known as OPEC . OPEC and OPEC  co=
untries agree on crude oil production levels at a country-level basis to co=
ordinate and limit their collective output. OPEC and OPEC  account for over=
 50% of global crude oil production.=E2=80=9D


  [10] Not literally *any* other context; there are, like, sports leagues.


