adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Who is selling all this underpriced life insurance?</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/35240647.256348/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vc=
GluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDQtMzAvYXBvbGxvLWhhZC1zb21lLWRlYXRoLWJldHM_Y21w=
aWQ9QkJEMDUwMjI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3N=
sZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwNTAyJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8=
524a319a23cBbb55bb38" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">talked on Tuesday</a> about a weird trade. Th=
e trade is: A person, usually an older person =E2=80=94=C2=A0call her Alice=
 =E2=80=94 takes out a $5 million life insurance policy, naming an investor=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0call him Bob =E2=80=94 as the beneficiary. Bob pays Alice a=
 fee for doing this =E2=80=94=C2=A0say 3% of the face value of the policy =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0and also=C2=A0pays=C2=A0the premiums on the policy. Eventual=
ly Alice dies, the insurance pays out, and Bob gets the money. If the death=
 benefit is higher than the premiums that Bob has paid over time =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0for instance, because Alice dies a week after taking out the policy =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0then Bob makes a profit. If the death benefit is lower than =
the premiums =E2=80=94=C2=A0for instance, because Alice lives to be 125 =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0then Bob loses money.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The thing=
 that most people find weird about this trade is the general ickiness of th=
e investor betting on Alice=E2=80=99s death. In fact, this trade =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0it is called STOLI, for stranger-originated life insurance =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0is not allowed in many places; we talked about it Tuesday because the=
 estate of an=C2=A0Alice=C2=A0(Martha Barotz)=C2=A0was suing a Bob (Apollo =
Global Management Inc.) to get the $5 million back.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">But I don=E2=80=99t mind ickiness, and the thing that I foun=
d weird about the trade was different. The thing that I found weird is: How=
 can Bob expect to make money on this trade? He is betting on Alice=E2=80=
=99s life span, with the life insurance company on the other side; why shou=
ld he expect to win that bet? Presumably Alice is a stranger to him and to =
the insurance company, and both of them can ask her for her medical history=
 and do physical exams.=C2=A0What is Bob=E2=80=99s informational advantage?=
=C2=A0I wrote:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On a deal like t=
his, the investor has to pay the insurance premiums, it has to pay the insu=
red a 3% commission to get her to take out the policy, it has to pay the ag=
ent a commission for signing her up,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#fo=
otnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border=
-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none=
 !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-bloc=
k;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0and of course it has to pay lawyers and take the risk that the po=
licy will be invalid. And yet there=E2=80=99s apparently still enough money=
 in it to make it a good, securitizable investment. Who is selling all this=
 underpriced life insurance?</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">S=
everal readers wrote in to answer=C2=A0this question, and the answer is ill=
uminating. Here=E2=80=99s how one reader put it:</p><blockquote><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">Some large fraction of life insurance policies are not op=
timally exercised.=C2=A0=C2=A0So traditionally life insurance companies sol=
d insurance that was significantly underpriced if the recipient was going t=
o optimally exercise it, and yet profitable because some reasonable fractio=
n of their clients let their policies lapse sub-optimally.</p></blockquote>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9COptimal exercise=E2=80=9D is a term f=
rom options markets and I suppose it is a little icky to apply it to life i=
nsurance. (You =E2=80=9Cexercise=E2=80=9D life insurance by dying, and it i=
s generally optimal to die as late as possible.) But the point is that a lo=
t of people take out life insurance policies, and then their circumstances =
change, they=C2=A0<em>stop paying the premiums </em>and the policy is cance=
led.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: t=
ransparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you take out a 20-year term life in=
surance policy, pay premiums for eight years, stop paying premiums, and the=
n die in Year 10, you will get no death benefit and the insurance company w=
ill keep your eight years of premiums. This is =E2=80=9Csuboptimal,=E2=80=
=9D for you, as a=C2=A0technical financial matter. But it might have been a=
 perfectly rational decision for you to let the insurance lapse: You took o=
ut the insurance thinking your heirs needed money when you died more than y=
ou needed the premiums while you were alive, and then your circumstances ch=
anged. Maybe you thought you needed 20 years of insurance to provide for yo=
ur minor children, but then they got child acting gigs and don=E2=80=99t ne=
ed the insurance money, and you=E2=80=99d rather spend the premiums while y=
ou=E2=80=99re alive.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the=C2=A0<em>insur=
ance company=C2=A0</em>doesn=E2=80=99t care about any of that; from the ins=
urance company=E2=80=99s perspective what happened is that it got eight yea=
rs of premiums and didn=E2=80=99t have to pay out when you died. You did no=
t exercise optimally. The insurance company is in an actuarial business; it=
 can predict what percentage of its customers will let their policies lapse=
. The percentage is large.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !importan=
t; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a> And in a competitive market, it can price this, and does.<a class=3D"f=
ootnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !impor=
tant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a> The amount you pay for a 20-year term life policy is calculated based =
on:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 1=
6px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The insurance company=E2=80=99=
s well-informed prediction of when you are likely to die,=C2=A0<em>and</em>=
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The insurance company=E2=80=99s w=
ell-informed prediction of when you are likely to stop paying premiums.</li=
></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bob, in our example, is no better at pre=
dicting Alice=E2=80=99s death than the insurance company is.<a class=3D"foo=
tnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !importa=
nt; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a> But there is an information asymmetry: The insurance company thinks th=
at Alice has, say, a 40% chance of letting the policy lapse before she dies=
, and Bob knows that the actual chance is 0%. He=E2=80=99s paying the premi=
ums, he=E2=80=99s a=C2=A0financial investor, he bought this policy as a bet=
, his circumstances are not going to change, he=E2=80=99s going to keep pay=
ing until he gets the death benefit.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#fo=
otnote-6" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border=
-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none=
 !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-bloc=
k;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a> The insurance company priced the policy at, intuitively, a 40% discoun=
t to its purely mortality-risk-based value, because it figured there was a =
40% chance of suboptimal lapse. That 40% discount is =E2=80=94 in expectati=
on, over hundreds of policies that he buys =E2=80=94 profit to Bob.</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A few points about this. One: It=E2=80=99s a big p=
art of why STOLI is often illegal. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbu=
siness.com/click/35240647.256348/aHR0cHM6Ly9jYXNldGV4dC5jb20vY2FzZS9lc3RhdG=
Utb2YtYmFyb3R6LXYtdmlkYS1sb25nZXZpdHktZnVuZC1scA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3=
2aba70a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgrou=
nd-color: #ccc;">Courts say</a> that insurance contracts are valid only if =
they are taken out for =E2=80=9Ca legitimate insurance purpose, such as est=
ate planning.=E2=80=9D Insurance companies price insurance based on the ass=
umption that real people are doing estate planning, and their circumstances=
 might change in ways that lead to suboptimal exercise. Insurance priced ba=
sed on a <em>pure bet=C2=A0</em>would be more expensive.=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In fact, there seems to have been a boom in STOLI in t=
he mid-2000s, as the secondary market for life insurance was ramping up, bu=
t it died=C2=A0 out by 2008. The trade we talked about Tuesday was originat=
ed in 2006; it=E2=80=99s cleaning up an old STOLI policy, not an active tra=
de. Part of the reason for this ramp-up was that, for insurance carriers an=
d brokers, STOLI <em>looked=C2=A0</em>like a good trade at the time: They g=
ot to write all these big insurance policies! Those policies looked=C2=A0pr=
ofitable, based on historical data. Then they realized they were all underp=
riced and shut it down.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Two: This problem i=
s not=C2=A0<em>solely=C2=A0</em>a feature of STOLI insurance. We talked on =
Tuesday about the broader business of investors buying life insurance polic=
ies; Apollo, for instance, manages billions of dollars=E2=80=99 worth of po=
licies. Most of those policies are=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>STOLI policies; t=
hey were taken out by real people for real insurance purposes, and then, wh=
en those peoples=E2=80=99 needs changed, they sold the policies to investor=
s. STOLI is frowned upon and often illegal and hard to collect on, but the =
broader secondary market for insurance policies is fine and legitimate and =
does pay out.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But it=E2=80=99s the sa=
me problem. Insurance companies bet that X% of their policies will lapse su=
boptimally. If there is a robust and well-advertised=C2=A0secondary market =
for the policies, then this estimate will be much too high: Everyone who ta=
kes out an insurance policy and decides to stop paying the premiums will=C2=
=A0<em>sell=C2=A0</em>the policy to an investor, for cash, rather than lett=
ing it lapse for nothing.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-7" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important=
; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[7]</span>
</a> And so not just STOLI policies, but=C2=A0<em>all=C2=A0</em>policies, w=
ill be underpriced. On Tuesday I quoted (in a footnote) <a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35240647.256348/aHR0cHM6Ly9zY2hvbGFyc=
