 need such a big house), and then you=E2=80=99ll have to pay back the loan.=
 The bank is stuck with its below-market loan, but not forever; even now, w=
hen mortgage rates are 7%, some people still go and pay off their 3% mortga=
ges. If they didn=E2=80=99t, things would be rough for the bank.</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If mortgages were always automatically assumable, the=
n when you sold your house you=E2=80=99d let the buyer assume your mortgage=
, and that 3% mortgage would remain outstanding for 30 years, and the bank =
would be stuck with it, and that would be worse for the bank, so it would h=
ave to charge you more for your mortgage to begin with.</p></blockquote><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The entire US mortgage system is priced off the f=
act that people suboptimally exercise their mortgage prepayment option: Peo=
ple are=C2=A0<em>constantly=C2=A0</em>prepaying 3% mortgages when mortgage =
rates are 7%, an insane financial decision=C2=A0<em>in isolation=C2=A0</em>=
but possibly perfectly rational for them=C2=A0<em>in real life.=C2=A0</em>(=
If you have to move, for a new job or a new relationship or just a nicer ho=
use, you will probably have to prepay your mortgage.) The average 30-year m=
ortgage actually lasts <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/c=
lick/35240647.256348/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc29maS5jb20vbGVhcm4vY29udGVudC9hdmVyYW=
