<tr>
<td class=3D"body-component__content" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; m=
so-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt; line-height: 150%; padding: 0 =
10px;">
<div id=3D"footnote-1" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[1] Actually the insurance company normally pa=
ys the agent, but the economic point stands: There are a lot of mouths to f=
eed here out of what is essentially a zero-sum bet between the insurance co=
mpany and the investor.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-2" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[2] That is the normal result in a term life p=
olicy. Other insurance products (universal life) have a savings component, =
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35240647.256348/aH=
R0cHM6Ly93d3cuaWlpLm9yZy9hcnRpY2xlL2lmLWktY2FudC1wYXktbXktcHJlbWl1bS13aGF0L=
XNob3VsZC1pLWRv/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd959da90" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">and you can</a> =
stop paying premiums and cash out the savings component (the =E2=80=9Csurre=
nder value=E2=80=9D of the policy). In either case though you are effective=
ly losing the actuarial value of your death benefit. I talk about term poli=
cies in the text because they are simpler to understand, but in reality mos=
t of the activity here is in universal life.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-3" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[3] Below, I quote a published estimate of 38%=
, but I have informally heard much higher numbers. Here is a <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35240647.256348/aHR0cHM6Ly9mYWN1=
bHR5LndoYXJ0b24udXBlbm4uZWR1L3dwLWNvbnRlbnQvdXBsb2Fkcy8yMDE2LzExL0luc3VyYW5=
jZTQxLnBkZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB260b26d8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" items=
cope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">2016 study</a> by Da=
niel Gottlieb and Kent Smetters finding lapse rates of 2.5% to 7% per year.=
</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-4" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[4] =E2=80=9CThere is substantial anecdotal ev=
idence that insurers take subsequent profits from lapses into account when =
setting their premiums,=E2=80=9D wrote <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/35240647.256348/aHR0cHM6Ly9mYWN1bHR5LndoYXJ0b24udXBlbm=
4uZWR1L3dwLWNvbnRlbnQvdXBsb2Fkcy8yMDE2LzExL0luc3VyYW5jZTQxLnBkZg/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cC260b26d8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;">Gottlieb and Smetters</a>. They provide so=
me numbers: =E2=80=9CThe Society of Actuaries 2006 Annual Meetings held a s=
ession on lapse-supported pricing that included presentations from actuarie=
s employed by several leading insurance companies and consultants. Kevin Ho=
ward, Vice President of Protective Life Insurance Company, for example, dem=
onstrated the impact of lapses on profit margins for a representative male =
client who bought a level-premium secondary guarantee universal life policy=
, with the premium set equal to the average amount paid by such males in Au=
gust 2006 in the company=E2=80=99s sample. Assuming a zero lapse rate, the =
insurer projected a substantial negative profit margin, equal to -12.8%. Ho=
wever, at a typical four percent lapse rate, the insurer=E2=80=99s projecte=
d profit margin was  13.6%, or a 26.4% increase relative to no lapsing.=E2=
=80=9D That is, the policy is priced at a level that would lose money for t=
he insurer, if every customer kept paying the premiums. But it makes money =
for the insurer, because many of them don=E2=80=99t.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-5" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[5] He=E2=80=99s also not much *worse*, becaus=
e he=E2=80=99s a price taker on the policy, and in a competitive market the=
 insurance company is going to price the policy based on its best estimate =
of her mortality risk.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-6" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[6] Realistically Bob is a fund, and even if h=
e runs into financial problems and can=E2=80=99t keep paying the premiums, =
he=E2=80=99ll sell the policy to someone else for its market value.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-7" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[7] At least in many cases, the investor will =
pay some nonzero amount of money for it, because it is underpriced, because=
 it was priced assuming suboptimal exercise. But there are exceptions: If y=
ou took out a term life policy when you were sickly and smoking and then go=
t incredibly fit, an investor might not pay you to take over the premiums.<=
/p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-8" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[8] See footnote 2. Lorde Martin also notes th=
at =E2=80=9CThe life insurance industry contributed to the emergence of the=
 life settlement industry by offering very low surrender value payments to =
people. One life settlement company claims that, on average, it has paid po=
licy owners about ten times the surrender value offered by the issuing insu=
rance company when the policy owner wanted to stop paying premiums. One tra=
de association reports that the average settlement is four to six times the=
 surrender value.=E2=80=9D</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-9" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[9] From today=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35240647.256348/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnRjLmd=
vdi9zeXN0ZW0vZmlsZXMvZnRjX2dvdi9wZGYvMjQxMDAwNGV4eG9ucGlvbmVlcmNvbXBsYWludH=
JlZGFjdGVkLnBkZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC4589095d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" =
itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">FTC complaint</=
a>: =E2=80=9COPEC was created in 1960 with the stated purpose to =E2=80=98c=
oordinate and unify the petroleum policies of its Member Countries and ensu=
re the stabilization of oil markets.=E2=80=99 OPEC has twelve member nation=
s: Saudi Arabia, Iran, Iraq, Kuwait, Venezuela, Indonesia, Libya, UAE, Alge=
ria, Nigeria, Equatorial Guinea, and Congo. Ten additional countries=E2=80=
=94including Russia=E2=80=94affiliated with OPEC in 2016 to create what is =
now known as OPEC . OPEC and OPEC  countries agree on crude oil production =
levels at a country-level basis to coordinate and limit their collective ou=
tput. OPEC and OPEC  account for over 50% of global crude oil production.=
=E2=80=9D</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-10" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ita=
lic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[10] Not literally *any* other context; there =
are, like, sports leagues.</p>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</td>
</tr>
